{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491158"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/847"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.5,0.29,0.03,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47478"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/847"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32194"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1287"},{"type":"tags","id":"1293"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12301"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47478"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents with a two-day history of dark coloured stool. He has not had any abdominal pain. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his pulse rate is 100/min and regular and blood pressure 130/80 mmHg. Rectal examination shows altered blood. His haemoglobin is 90 g/L (135-180). Gastroscopy and colonoscopy obtain good views of the upper and lower digestive tracts, with no cause found for the bleeding. One day later his haemoglobin is 70 g/L and he receives a transfusion of four units of blood. His pulse rate is now 120/min and blood pressure 96/70 mmHg. He has passed multiple bowel actions containing altered blood in the last 2 hours.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Following resuscitation, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat endoscopy and colonoscopy","CT angiography","Video capsule endoscopy","Push enteroscopy","MR enterography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is actively bleeding. Some 90-95% of cases of gastrointestinal bleeding are either from the upper or the lower digestive tract, with the remaining small percentage arising from the small bowel. In other words, in appropriate circumstances and without torrential haemorrhage to obscure the view, either endoscopy or colonoscopy will be all that is necessary to identify the site of a bleed - and usually be able to get the bleeding under control. The normal endoscopy and colonoscopy finding suggest that the source of the bleed may well be in the small bowel. Following resuscitation the most expedient way identifying the source is \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiography\u003C/strong\u003E. This can be followed by conventional angiography to treat the bleeding point (vessel). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECapsule endoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be the most appropriate next investigation in a haemodynamically stable patient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPush enteroscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is an extended upper endoscopy performed with a long endoscope. It allows for the evaluation and treatment of lesions in the proximal small bowel. Push enteroscopy is recommended for management of proximal small bowel lesions identified following video capsule endoscopy.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance (MR) enterography\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in patients who have had extensive investigation for suspected small bowel bleeds with no identifiable source but worsening anaemia. It is not appropriate in this acute setting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active bleeding in the midgut will need some form of radiological intervention to define its source.","CTA requires bleeding of 0.5ml/min to detect active blush so should be used in the acute setting"],"references":["Alzoubaidi D, Lovat LB, Haidry R. Management of non-variceal upper gastrointestinal bleeding: where are we in 2018? Frontline Gastroenterology 2019;10:35-42. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30651955/","Gerson LB, Fidler JL, Cave DR, Leighton JA. ACG Clinical Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Small Bowel Bleeding. Am J Gastroenterol. 2015;110(9):1265-87. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26303132/","Ohmiya N. Management of obscure gastrointestinal bleeding: Comparison of guidelines between Japan and other countries. Digestive Endoscopy. 2020;32(2):204-218. Available online: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31596970/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32194"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"847"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32194"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-23T21:36:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-23T21:36:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"847"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47478"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null